Summaries

Five sample summaries

[1] The speaker talked about Colombia as a perfect place, rich in nature. However, he also talked about the disadvantages of not being peaceful. He said that 5.7 million people have lost their homes so far, making it one of the largest refugee populations in the world. The speaker also said that more than 220,000 people have been killed in this conflict. The government implemented a plan to put up "Christmas lights" against the guerrillas. This tree led to the disarmament of 331 guerrillas, which was 5% of their fighting force at the time. Next to the lights, he wrote, "If Christmas can come to the jungle, you can go home too. Let's disarm. Anything is possible at Christmas." How did he come up with this method? It goes back four years. Four years ago, the government visited the speaker and said that they needed a "communication strategy." The speaker thought that this was a great opportunity to resolve the conflict, so he spoke to the guerrillas who had surrendered, understood the current situation, and ultimately came to the conclusion that they should put up lights.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         
[2] According to Jose Miguel Sokoloff, Colombia is a country that has a nice personality, a lot of animals and nature. On the other hand, it also has a guerrilla organization that has been around for over 50 years, so Jose hasnt experienced peace since he was there. The organization is part of the revolutionary army of Colombia, and they are doing some illegal activity, such as trafficking, violence, and terrorism. 5.7 million people were taken away from their living place, and 220 thousand people died in conflicts. One of the peaceful solutions is the illumination in Christmas. 4 years ago, he was asked to think what to do to disarm the guerrillas, without a military solution. He talked with guerrillas, so Jose understood what happened there, and that they were also trapped in the army. Next, he started the radio program to listen to the army's stories, and speak to them as human. One captain said that tolerance makes us stronger, and cooperated to set the Christmas trees. As a result, 17 thousand of the army surrendered. Jose believes that advertising is the most effective way to tell someone.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[3] Colombia has one of the oldest guerrilla organisations in the world, called the FARC. Due to that guerrilla organisation, Colombia has never felt peace until now. Specifically, in 50 years, 5.7 million people have been displaced from their homes in Colombia and more than 220,000 people in the search for a peaceful solution, Jose came up with a new support called Christmas Lights. This support was highly effective and enabled him to disarm 5% of the guerrilla organisation's guerrilla soldiers. He was also asked by the government to come up with a means of communication to get the guerrilla soldiers out of the jungle. He engaged in dialogue with a number of former guerrilla soldiers in order to come up with a means of doing so. From this he realised that although the guerrilla soldiers were capturing people, they were also being captured by the organisation. He then came up with the idea of Christmas lights, based on his analysis that more soldiers disarm at Christmas. This approach of reminding soldiers of their humanity has been effective. For example, objects given to the guerrilla soldiers by their loved ones were washed into the river, and the guerrilla soldiers' mothers gave them photographs of the guerrilla soldiers as children and pasted them up. During the World Cup, we called out on TV that there was a place for guerrilla soldiers to come back. Thanks to his activities, 17,000 soldiers were disarmed. His activities inspired people to think about disarmament.
[4]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   
[5]

Opinions

five sample opinions

[1] I think guerrillas would suffer. It is because they must go to war, trade drugs and not fall in love. They are very sad things and I cannot imagine doing it. Becoming guerrilla makes many people very sad, but this problem continues. I want to solve it. In addition, the speaker who conducted the radio strategy is very nice. It solved people and peoples minds. I want to become like him.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
[2] I had never thought of weakening guerrilla organizations through Christmas trees and illuminations, so it was refreshing to hear his ideas and activities. At first, I was surprised to hear that instead of simply telling guerrilla organizations to "stop" or attacking them, he was appealing for them to disarm in a different way. That way is a quite new one. However, when I learned that so many people had left the guerrilla organization because of this activity, I realized the usefulness of this method. I didn't know much about Colombian guerrilla organizations and the activities against them, so I wanted to find out more myself.                                                                       
[3] I had thought that legal and political solutions were the shortcut to peace negotiations, but I was surprised to find that communication strategies had a surprisingly large impact. Although many of the tactics were emotional, such as Operation Christmas Tree and mothers using photos of their children to encourage guerrillas to retire, they had a great impact on guerrillas, and were particularly effective strategies for lower-ranking soldiers. Today, SNS still has a great influence, and in North Korea, China, and Russia, the use of SNS is restricted, creating a situation where it is difficult to communicate with the outside world. We need to actively think about how to approach such situations.   
[4] I got very emotional because there are wonderful movements to solve the problem of war. And also I love Christmas, it was my favorite way. I guess the government should do these movements, but I found a new way of citizens active participation. And I thought there are more ways to think about wars for everyone. Id like to think more and more in my own way. What is more, there is also a track record as speakers could make guerrillas demobilized for about 17000, so the government needs to help their activities. Working together makes a big difference than before.                                                                                                                                        
[5] I was very surprised that there were such dangerous guerrilla organisations in Colombia. I thought that these guerrilla soldiers would be feared and shunned by the country, but I was very impressed that the country as a whole is trying to solve the problem, as when many media, including TV and radio, called out to the guerrilla soldiers during the World Cup. In particular, he felt that what he said about soldiers being captured by an organisation could be said of guerrilla soldiers in any country. Also, his activities were very unique and firmly effective. I thought that if such activities were more widespread, it would bring us closer to peace, as there are many armed organisations in the world.
